message: To reliably score 60 points, follow these steps: 1. Use the 'stove' on any 'raw protein' (e.g., raw beans, raw fish, raw beef, raw bacon) to get a 'cooked protein' (value 20). 2. Combine the 'cooked protein' with a 'grain' (e.g., tortilla, wheat, bread) to create a 2-component item (value 40). 3. Add one 'vegetable' (e.g., cucumber, mushroom, lettuce, potato) to the 2-component item to create a 3-component dish (value 60). Crucially, *do not* add a fourth ingredient; this will almost always result in an 'overcomplicated' item with a value of 0 or less. Also, using the 'stove' on a 3-component item often 'overcooks' it and reduces its value. I was not able to discover how to reach 80 or 100 points, but 60 is consistent if you follow this pattern.

message: Focus on cooking proteins and vegetables with the ğŸ”¥ stove first; they usually yield 20 points each. Combining two cooked proteins makes 40 points. Combining a cooked protein with a cooked vegetable often makes 60 points. To reach 80 points, combine a 40-point protein medley with a 20-point cooked vegetable, or a 60-point protein-vegetable blend with another 20-point cooked vegetable. Be cautious with grains like corn, as cooking them didn't increase value and further processing could lead to negative scores.
